{
  "title": "Observing CLI Tools Using FastAPI with Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide demonstrates how to integrate command-line interface (CLI) tools into a FastAPI application for seamless execution and response handling in Python 3.12+.",

  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI is a modern, high-performance web framework for building APIs with Python.",
    "In this example, we will integrate an external CLI tool into our FastAPI application to demonstrate its usage.",
    "We will use `subprocess` module for running the command and handling the output.",
    "Python 3.12+ is required for some of the new features used in this explanation."
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\nimport subprocess\n\nasync def execute_cli(command: str):\n    process = await asyncio.create_subprocess_shell(subprocess.Popen(command, shell=True, stdout=subprocess.PIPE))\n    output, _ = await process.communicate()\n    return output.decode('utf-8')\n```"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI, HTTPException\napp = FastAPI()\n\n@app.get('/run_cli/<command>')\nasync def run_cli(command: str):\n    try:\n        result = await execute_cli(command)\n        return {'result': result}\n    except Exception as e:\n        raise HTTPException(status_code=500, detail=str(e))\n```"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "Python versions prior to 3.12 may not support the specific features used in this example.",
    "FastAPI version requirements: The examples provided use FastAPI v0.76.0, but you can adapt them to other versions."
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "Be aware that integrating CLI tools may expose your application's security risks if not properly validated and sanitized.",
